      "desc": "Primary enclosures.",
      "narrative": "On 12/11/2025, the facility received in shipment an 8-year-old, Southern Ground-Hornbill. According to facility\nrepresentatives, the animal care staff opened the shipping container within its quarantine stall enclosure to monitor the\nbird and allow it to settle into its enclosure. A short time later an animal care team member returned to check on the bird\nand called for assistance when he noticed the bird managed to escape from its stall to a next-door stall. Before the team\ncould enter the stall to capture the bird, it quickly flew up to an upper rafter then to a nearby empty stall and flew out\nthrough an open door. Following extensive search efforts, the bird was recaptured four days later outside of facility\nproperty at a nearby location. According to a discussion with a facility veterinarian and records review, the bird was\nexamined and determined to be in good health with no adverse effects or injuries following its escape. Unsecured\nenclosures, doors or openings do not safely contain birds and may lead to escape and potential distress, injury, and non-\nrecovery. The facility has implemented corrective measures to maintain security of enclosures and prevent reoccurrence.\nPrimary enclosures must be designed and constructed of suitable materials so they are structurally sound, are kept in\ngood repair, and maintained so they will contain the birds securely.\nCorrect from this day, 01/26/2026, forward.\nThis inspection and exit interview were conducted with facility representatives.\nn"
    }
  ],
  "narrative": "3.153(a)(1)(iii) \n   \nPrimary enclosures. \nOn 12/11/2025, the facility received in shipment an 8-year-old, Southern Ground-Hornbill. According to facility \nrepresentatives, the animal care staff opened the shipping container within its quarantine stall enclosure to monitor the \nbird and allow it to settle into its enclosure. A short time later an animal care team member returned to check on the bird \nand called for assistance when he noticed the bird managed to escape from its stall to a next-door stall. Before the team \ncould enter the stall to capture the bird, it quickly flew up to an upper rafter then to a nearby empty stall and flew out \nthrough an open door. Following extensive search efforts, the bird was recaptured four days later outside of facility \nproperty at a nearby location. According to a discussion with a facility veterinarian and records review, the bird was \nexamined and determined to be in good health with no adverse effects or injuries following its escape. Unsecured \nenclosures, doors or openings do not safely contain birds and may lead to escape and potential distress, injury, and non-\nrecovery. The facility has implemented corrective measures to maintain security of enclosures and prevent reoccurrence. \nPrimary enclosures must be designed and constructed of suitable materials so they are structurally sound, are kept in \ngood repair, and maintained so they will contain the birds securely.  \n \nCorrect from this day, 01/26/2026, forward. \n \nThis inspection and exit interview were conducted with facility representatives. \n \n n",
